<section class="article">
  <div class="container-narrow">
    <article class="prose">

      <h2 style="border-top:none;margin-top:0;padding-top:0;" id="protections">Where the law protects you</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>At work.</strong> Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 prohibits employers from refusing to hire, firing, or mistreating you because of your race, national origin, or religion.<sup>1</sup></li>
        <li><strong>In housing.</strong> The Fair Housing Act prohibits discrimination in rental, sales, lending, and other housing-related services based on race, color, national origin, religion, sex, disability, and family status.<sup>2</sup></li>
        <li><strong>In public places.</strong> Title II of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 protects your right to equal service in hotels, restaurants, stores, and public transportation.<sup>3</sup></li>
        <li><strong>At school.</strong> Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964 prohibits discrimination in schools and programs receiving federal funds.<sup>4</sup></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="what-to-do">If you experience discrimination</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Keep a detailed record</strong> of any evidence — emails, texts, photos, dates, times, and witness names.</li>
        <li><strong>Report it to the right federal agency:</strong>
          <ul>
            <li>Employment discrimination → <strong>EEOC</strong> (Equal Employment Opportunity Commission)</li>
            <li>Housing discrimination → <strong>HUD</strong> (Department of Housing and Urban Development)</li>
            <li>School discrimination → <strong>Department of Education, Office for Civil Rights</strong></li>
          </ul>
        </li>
        <li><strong>Consult an attorney.</strong> Many lawyers offer free initial consultations for discrimination cases.</li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-title">A bank cannot close your account just because you are Iranian</div>
        <p>U.S. banks cannot lawfully close an account solely because of national origin — that would be prohibited national-origin discrimination. However, banks have wide discretion to manage perceived risk and may close accounts citing those reasons. If a bank closes your account, ask in writing for the specific reason. If you believe national origin played a role, file a complaint with the Consumer Financial Protection Bureau (<a href="https://consumerfinance.gov" target="_blank" rel="noopener">consumerfinance.gov</a>) and consult a civil-rights attorney. More on banking and Iran sanctions in the <a href="sanctions.html">U.S. Sanctions on Iran</a> section.</p>
      </div>

      <h2 id="hate-incidents">Hate incidents &amp; harassment</h2>
      <p>If you experience harassment or a hate incident — slurs, threats, vandalism, or violence motivated by national origin or religion — you can also:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Report the incident to local police if there is an immediate safety concern.</li>
        <li>Report it to the FBI’s civil-rights division if you believe it may constitute a federal hate crime.</li>
        <li>Document everything — photos, messages, witness names, times.</li>
        <li>Reach out to civil-rights organizations that track and respond to such incidents in the Iranian American community.</li>
      </ul>

      <details class="citations">
        <summary>Sources — Discrimination</summary>
        <ol>
          <li>Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, 42 U.S.C. § 2000e.</li>
          <li>Fair Housing Act, 42 U.S.C. § 3601 et seq.</li>
          <li>Title II of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, 42 U.S.C. § 2000a.</li>
          <li>Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, 42 U.S.C. § 2000d.</li>
        </ol>
      </details>

